    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nThe docs for `vim.wo` currently say the following:\n\n```\nvim.wo[{winid}][{bufnr}]\n    Get or set window-scoped |options| for the window with handle {winid} and\n    buffer with number {bufnr}. Like `:setlocal` if setting a |global-local|\n    option or if {bufnr} is provided, like `:set` otherwise. If {winid} is\n    omitted then the current window is used. Invalid {winid}, {bufnr} or key\n    is an error.\n\n    Note: only {bufnr} with value `0` (the current buffer in the window) is\n    supported.\n```\n\nThis is confusing for two different reasons:\n\n1. Why can I index using `{bufnr}` if only 0 is supported ?\n    - The purpose of `vim.wo` is to set window-local options. As far as I understand, a window will always be tied to a specific buffer. Why would we need to query a certain buffer for a given window ?\n2. If I can index using both IDs, how can I \"omit\" the winid ?\n    - If I want to set a window-local option for all windows related to buffer `{bufnr}`, how can I access that ? Is it `vim.wo[{bufnr}].foo = bar` (which errors out currently on master) ? Or maybe `vim.wo[][{bufnr}].foo = bar` which I believe is not a valid Lua syntax.\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\nnvim --clean\n:h vim.wo\n(return to editable buffer)\n:lua vim.wo[vim.api.nvim_get_current_buf()].wrap = true\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nThere are two ways to solve that issue.\n\n1. Remove the `{bufnr}` indexing from the docs, and only allow `vim.wo` to be indexed by a window ID (easy to do).\n2. Actually implement accessing `vim.wo` from other buffer numbers than 0 (a lot more work).\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\nNVIM v0.12.0-dev-555+g93925fe020\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nno (lua issue)\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nFedora 42 KDE Edition\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nwezterm\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nxterm-256color\n\n### Installation\n\nLatest master branch build.",
